<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Somtimes</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I will stay in character when using /tell, but not normally.<br>
<br>
My reasoning is simple: one tool is to aid Role Play, while another tool is to aid <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> GAMEPLAY</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
/ooc, /acution, /tell, /guild, and any other channel that doesn't require my character to be in the same group, or more importantly the same zone, are gameplay tools, and RP doesn't need to be used there. Indeed, someone who always speaks using /auction, but stays in character the entire time, will annoy me FAR more then someone in my group who talks OOC all the time. The point is, there are tools for RP, and tools for gameplay.<br>
<br>
Likewise for this issue concerning grouping. I play a Halfling Paladin, and I am in a very supportive guild made up of only small races (includes Wood Elves). I never intentionally try to group with Dark Elves, Trolls, Ogres, or Iksars, but I HAVE been in groups with them, and have even invited them when I was leading a group. This is a gameplay issue, period. If I CAN do without them, I do, and when I do group with them, I use emotes, etc. indicating my unease of the situation. Indeed, some of the best RPing I've encountered comes from this very situation...how boring does RP become when you simply LOVE everyone in the group? It certainly takes alot less skill.<br>
<br>
Either way, if the choice comes down to accepting that Dark Elf or that Ogre into the group, or be forced to solo or limited to hunting blues/greens, in my opinion, it isn't even a choice. That is the same thing as choosing between playing or not. If advancement isn't important to you, then to each their own. I fail to see how anyone who plays this game can think this way, but that is their choice.<br>
<br>
So, as to &quot;pushing the envelope,&quot; it is all a matter of gameplay. If you can still play the game, AND group in a manner that makes &quot;sense,&quot; GREAT! However, choosing to limit your gameplay because you &quot;don't like&quot; Dark Elves is a bit ridiculous in a game like EQ. Grouping is hard enough, and getting a GOOD group is that much more difficult; why put meaningless limits on yourself? After all, you ARE paying for this. Finally, as I stated previously, grouping with races you have a dislike for opens up FAR AND AWAY more RP opprotunites then grouping with races you would obviously have little problem with. Indeed, what is there to really RP in that situation? All you see is the &quot;good&quot; side of the character...bring in that Dark Elf Shadowknight, and prepare to see a very <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> different</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> side of this normally lovable Halfling Paladin...THAT is Role Playing...and yet we can still play the game. What a concept.<br>
<br>
~Rose<br>
