<br>
No one could say &quot;There is no way a Circle could ever group with a Square, everyone knows that. If you do it you are not RP&quot; withtu looking a little foolish. You and I could rationally differ in opinion on what the motivations of a Square was. It is very hard when we all &quot;know&quot; how a good should behave. <br>
<br>
Since we all intrinsically know what &quot;good&quot; and &quot;evil&quot; mean it is too easy to jump down someone's throat for departing from our own notions of how they should play.  This limits the ability to roleplay to a very narrowly constrained set of acceptable actions. The world is much to complex to be bound by these limits.<br>
<br>
EQ puts us into groups and then precludes us from doing what that group would do. What truely &quot;good&quot; person would not step in to help their local militia when an enemy attacks them. We are not only powerless to help, we are subject to punishment for doing something that might help (i.e. guard training, etc). What &quot;evil&quot; person would not find a lower level person and delight in torturing them for the pure enjoyment of it? Not only would that person be blacklisted, but it is really not even possible to do. <br>
<br>
If RP is simply defined as leaving the &quot;real&quot; world behind and jumping into EQ then most people would go along. It is only when someone attempts to impose a set of expected behaviors onto us that most of us object. If your necro wants to group with a pally go for it. Human motivations are far to complex to put into simplistic little niches like &quot;Good&quot; and &quot;Evil&quot;, why should our toons be any different?<br>
<br>
So, if we throw off the notions of &quot;good&quot; and &quot;evil&quot; and think of circle and square then perhaps more people will have the freedom to get outside their constrictive bounds and have some fun.<br>
<br>
Or, we can just kill giant rats.<br>
<br>
